## Non-negotiable rules

1. Do not modify historical migration logic unless the task explicitly requires a documented repair.
2. Do not regenerate missing Designers blindly.
3. Do not delete, rename, reorder, or archive old migrations unless the task explicitly proves it is safe and updates all docs.
4. Do not change `ApplicationDbContextModelSnapshot.cs` unless the task is specifically about snapshot reconciliation.
5. Do not mix migration governance with unrelated runtime/feature work.
6. Do not assume a no-Designer migration is accidental; classify it first.
7. Do not allow undocumented migration states to remain.
8. Bias toward preservation, documentation, and validator truth.
9. If counts change, update every relevant source of truth.
10. If a migration is suspiciously large, treat it as possible snapshot drift and stop/escalate.

---

## Governance duties (order of thinking)

A. Is this a normal EF migration?  
B. Is this an intentional script-only migration?  
C. Is this an accidental incomplete migration?  
D. Is this snapshot drift?  
E. Are docs, manifest, validator, and CI aligned?

---

## Official migration creation path

From repo root: `.\backend\scripts\create-migration.ps1 -MigrationName "DescriptiveName"`  
From backend: `.\scripts\create-migration.ps1 -MigrationName "DescriptiveName"`

**Good names:** AddOrderStatusChecklist, AddPasswordResetTokens, AddWorkflowInstanceIndexes, AddJobExecutionMetadata.  
**Bad names:** temp, test, fix, migration1, newmigration, wip, aaa. Warn and improve poor names before proceeding.

---

## Validation

Always use: `backend/scripts/validate-migration-hygiene.ps1`

If validator fails: stop, explain why, align repo/docs/manifest/expectations before continuing.  
If validator warns: do not ignore; inspect and document the decision.

---

## New migrations

**CASE 1 — main `.cs` + `.Designer.cs`:** Treat as normal EF migration. Ensure name acceptable, validator passes, migration not unexpectedly huge (if huge, flag snapshot drift). Update docs only if baseline counts change.

**CASE 2 — main `.cs` only:** Do not assume error. Check: intentionally script-only? Real domain/schema intent? In manifest? Counts/docs updated? If intentional: classify as script-only, update manifest and counts and validator, preserve. If accidental: document, do not blindly repair, escalate.

---

## Script-only migrations

Ensure each is in `EF_NO_DESIGNER_MIGRATIONS_MANIFEST.md`, counts reflect it, validator expected count reflects it, runbook explains. Script-only must be fully documented or rejected.

---

## Snapshot drift

If a generated migration is unusually large, has many CreateTable operations, or seems to recreate schema: **STOP.** Treat as snapshot drift risk. Do not commit casually. Document suspicion, point to snapshot reconciliation docs, recommend dedicated sync or re-baseline. Large migrations are governance events.

---

## PR / review governance

Enforce: official script or EF path? Both `.cs` and `.Designer.cs` unless intentionally script-only? Validator passes? Acceptable name? Not unexpectedly large? No historical migrations edited without explicit approved purpose? Counts and docs aligned? If historical migrations edited without approval: stop, reject, document.

---

## When counts change

Update at minimum: validator script, migration hygiene doc, no-Designer manifest, final cleanup decision, future authoring rules, runbook, PR checklist, any impacted full audit/baseline docs. Never allow count drift between docs and repo.

---

## Clean up / fix requests

**Clean up:** Do not delete history because it is old. Classify as active EF, intentional script-only, ambiguous preserve, or safe archive only if proven. Bias toward preservation.

**Fix:** Determine category (missing Designer on new, undocumented script-only, validator baseline mismatch, snapshot drift, historical defect, manifest/docs inconsistency). Solve the actual governance problem.

---

## Required output style

When completing migration governance tasks, provide: (1) Executive summary, (2) Exact files changed, (3) Whether migration counts changed, (4) Whether manifest changed, (5) Whether validator baseline changed, (6) Whether any migration files changed, (7) Final authoritative counts, (8) Whether validator passes, (9) What remains deferred, (10) Clear next action. Be explicit; use exact migration IDs when relevant.

---

## One-line governance rule

Every migration must end in one of two explicit, documented states: normal EF migration with Designer, or intentional script-only recorded in the manifest and reflected in all counts, validation, and operational docs.

**Bias:** Truth over convenience; preservation over deletion; documentation over assumption; validator accuracy over stale baselines; explicit classification over silent drift.
